From: conda-forge
Subject: [PATCH] Disable process job objects on Windows to avoid Azure DevOps conflicts

Azure DevOps runs builds in a job object. When GHC's builderMainLoop tries to
create nested job objects for child processes, it can fail with "Invalid argument"
due to job object nesting restrictions or conflicts with the CI environment.

This patch disables process job tracking on Windows by making enableProcessJobs
a no-op. This fixes the "builderMainLoop: invalid argument" error on Azure CI.

The job object feature was added to fix GHC #16450, but causes issues in CI
environments that already use job objects for process management.

diff --git a/compiler/GHC/SysTools/Process.hs b/compiler/GHC/SysTools/Process.hs
--- a/compiler/GHC/SysTools/Process.hs
+++ b/compiler/GHC/SysTools/Process.hs
@@ -38,10 +38,14 @@ import GHC.Utils.TmpFs

 -- | Enable process jobs support on Windows if it can be expected to work (e.g.
 -- @process >= 1.6.9.0@).
+--
+-- NOTE: Disabled for conda-forge builds. Azure DevOps runs builds inside a
+-- job object, and creating nested job objects fails with "Invalid argument".
+-- See GHC #16450 for the original issue that motivated this feature.
 enableProcessJobs :: CreateProcess -> CreateProcess
 #if defined(MIN_VERSION_process)
-enableProcessJobs opts = opts { use_process_jobs = True }
+enableProcessJobs opts = opts  -- Disabled: conflicts with Azure DevOps job objects
 #else
 enableProcessJobs opts = opts
 #endif
